I was racking my brain about the seeming wizard problems, trying to find a logical explanation for this other than: &quot;Verant hates us&quot;.<br>
<br>
I've noticed that most wizards are fairly formulaic.  We all wear roughly similar equipment, because we all go for roughly the same goals on item attributes... we all have 200 int within a few points... we all belong to a community which already developed a pretty clear opinion of the best ways to equip and play a wizard.<br>
<br>
Is it possible that the thing behind this is that only a few wizards (or none?) have figured out how to do it right?  What if everyone's missing something about how to set up your wizard to be effective, and that's why Verant isn't fixing anything: because nothing's broke, just undiscovered...<br>
<br>
<br>
Do our problems go away if we max our int to 255?  What about other stats - even from Verant themselves I've seen conflicting answers on the true purpose of some stats like dex and agi... and we know they don't keep up in internal wizard mechanics well... does some &quot;non-caster&quot; stat actually help us in some way?  What about hp/ac?  Is it possible that the formula for group effectiveness involves getting lots of both and being an overnuking powerburner who can take hits?<br>
<br>
The above are just random last minute thoughts, I doubt any of them are it.  But I just want to know - in the past, have people scientifically tested wizards this way to determine that there's not something we're missing?<br>
<br>
