<br>
From the beginning, Wizards and Wars defined the baseline for the 3 prime classes, fighter/healer/caster.  When Wizards extreme powers in beta were cut back, fighters moved to the front.  Also, looking at the stats on how many people primarily play what classes, fighters chars are the vast majority.  Thus, fighters need healers and vica-versa, leaving a very small minority of casters having to beg around for group members.  This means we ended up having to group on their terms.  The best way for fighters to group and hunt has been tested and firmed up over the months and years.  Now, perhaps we have all lost the ability to think outside the box. <br>
<br>
Sure, some encounters clearly require tank-based single target approaches.  But other approaches have also become proven. Many guilds and groups before us had tried and tested numerous approaches to things like Vox in order to learn what would take her down, and what wouldn't.  Mass AE pulls in Seb, Karnor, etc.  have also proven to be hugely successful. <br>
<br>
All this suggests that there are likely other ways we can apply our skills and spells to new situations and combinations. Certainly Warriors eventually discovered the whopping benefits they recieve from having a Shaman in their group using certain spells at specialized times. Similarly, we are probably missing some combination of abilities and tactics simply because many of us have succumb to the insistance of the melee-class world that we are only useful in the ways that they dictate, or in the false belief that everything new has already been tried and discarded by someone before us. <br>
<br>
One reason many such explorations are likely to be pushed down before birth is that even here among your fellow wizards, many of them will ridicule and rabidly insist that anything that does not seem possible to them is impossible--that anything that does not seem normal to them is useless. Still, there are pleanty of others who would support thinking and wondering, new trials and experiments. We can only hope that those who find revelations bother to return to these pages and share them.<br>
<br>
Kel,55,Ixtlan,Veeshan <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ueanaminelessedil.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eanamin Elessedil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/2/01 5:04 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A different thought on wizard problems</span><hr size=1> They won't <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>ever</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> (read as: in the foreseeable future) make the INT soft cap go above 200 for non-L60 players.  It's just not gonna happen.  Here's why:<br>
<br>
If they did that, there would be absolutely <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NO</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> reason - none whatsoever - to play anything other than an Erudite as a wizard.  You'd be utterly foolish to choose otherwise in that situation, whereas now, pretty much any other race is still a viable base race for a wizard.  As it is now, the Erudites already have a huge advantage, since they can reach 200 INT far more easily than the other races, letting them wear that much more +mana gear.<br>
<br>
Yeah, you can point to Ogres as having the highest STR of any of the warrior races and say that that makes them the &quot;perfect&quot; race for a warrior, and that you'd be foolish to choose any other race for a warrior, but warriors are FAR more dependant on equipment than is a wizard - the big difference with them lies in armor and weapons, not in base STR...<br>
<br>
Now I stated that they aren't going to be doing that for non-L60 players, but when Shadows of Luclin comes out, they will be allowing non-level-based advancement...  Perhaps that means that SoL-enabled L60 wizards can increase their INT soft cap?  Who knows.<br>
<br>
Just my thoughts. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=zestifan>Zestifan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/2/01 7:06 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A different thought on wizard problems</span><hr size=1> They're hinting at some type of specialization or skill-based increases for high level players in Luclin.  I don't know if you have to reach 60 or not to do it, but most likely you do since they're not raising the level cap.<br>
<br>
Too bad this isn't like in Diablo 2 where a sorcerer can specialize in ice, fire or lightning or a mixture of all three elements.  A soloer mainly goes after ice and grouping sorcs will generally do fire with a little ice and lightning thrown in.  That flexibility meant that alot of sorcs had varyings strengths and weakness and ways of fighting.<br>
<br>
The ideal magic system to me would be skill-based where you *chose* a primary casting ability and a lesser secondary.  Like primary=nuking and secondary=summoning or primary=nuking and secondary=mind control.  Your title would be named after your primary ability.  Besides higher skill you'd also have a bonus attached to your primary.  Your primary would be 75% better than your secondary.<br>
<br>
What I like about UO is while the magic system is the same for everyone, you can choose to raise or lower skills through practice.  If you decided you wanted to learn a new combat skill you could let one skill atrophy and build up your new one. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uvikano.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vikano</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/2/01 4:08 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> dex uses</span><hr size=1> Dex does seem to affect crit hits for warriors. Was grouped with a dwarf warrior who was hitting for crits maybe every 4 or so shots. It was insane. As a group we asked him how he was managing it and he said it was because he kept his dex up very high. This isn't a study, but if he knew what he was talking about (and he was landing crits way more than any tank I've every seen) dex affects crit frequency.<br>
